# How it works:
#   - Intercepts process.stdout.write
#   - Ink renders (sync blocks with \x1b[?2026h) are BUFFERED, not written
#   - Only the LATEST frame is kept (previous frames discarded)
#   - Flush triggers:
#     (a) User types (stdin data) → next render writes immediately
#         (user is at the prompt/bottom, viewport follows naturally)
#     (b) 5 seconds of no new renders → auto-flush
#         (Claude finished, show final state)
#   - Non-sync writes pass through immediately
#
# Why this works:
#   Windows Terminal bug microsoft/terminal#14774 causes viewport to jump
#   on ANY cursor positioning. By not writing to stdout during active work,
#   the viewport stays wherever the user scrolled. When the user types
#   (returning to the prompt at the bottom), rendering resumes normally.
#
# Trade-off:
#   Screen is frozen during active Claude work. User sees the result
#   when Claude pauses or they type. Spinner/progress not visible during work.
